{{italictitle}}
The '''''Chronicle of Cambridge''''' or '''''Cambridge Chronicle''''', also known as the '''''Tarʾīkh Jazīrat Ṣiqilliya''''' ("History of the Island of Sicily"), is a short, anonymous [[Middle Ages|medieval]] chronicle covering the years 827–965. It is the earliest native Sicilian chronicle of the [[emirate of Sicily]],<ref>{{cite encyclopedia |title=Islamic Palermo and the Dār al-Islām: Politics, Society and the Economy (from the mid-9th Century to the mid-11th Century) |first=Annliese |last=Nef |publisher=Brill |year=2013 |pages=39–60 |encyclopedia=A Companion to Medieval Palermo: The History of a Mediterranean City from 600 to 1500}}</ref> and was written from the perspective of a Sicilian Christian of the 10th or 11th century.<ref>{{cite book |title=Muslims and Christians in Norman Sicily: Arabic-Speakers and the End of Islam |first=Alexander |last=Metcalfe |publisher=Routledge |year=2013 |page=9}}</ref> It survives in two versions: a [[Byzantine Greek|Greek]] version in two manuscripts and an [[Arabic script|Arabic]] version in one. For years only the Arabic text kept in [[Cambridge University Library]] was known, but in 1890 a Greek redaction was discovered. The Greek texts are found in the [[Vatican Library]] and the [[Bibliothèque nationale de France]] (Codex Parisinus Graecus 920).<ref name=Engtrans>{{cite web |first=Alexander |last=Metcalfe |url=http://www.medievalsicily.com/Docs/02_Islamic/Cambridge%20Chronicle.pdf |title=The Cambridge Chronicle |website=Medieval Sicily |accessdate=10 March 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |first=Paul Julius |last=Alexander |title=The Byzantine Apocalyptic Tradition |page=85 |year=1985 |publisher=University of California Press}}</ref> It has been translated into English,<ref name=Engtrans/> Italian<ref>{{cite journal |editor-first=Giuseppe |editor-last=Cozza-Luzi |year=1890 |title=La cronaca siculo-saracena di Cambridge con doppio testo greco scoperto in codici contemporanei delle Bibliotheca Vaticana e Parigina |journal=Documenti per Servire alla Storia di Sicilia, Pubblicati e Cura della Società Siciliana per la Storia Patria |issue=4th ser., vol. 2 |location=Palermo}}</ref> and French.<ref>{{cite encyclopedia |first=A. A. |last=Vasiliev |authorlink=Alexander Vasiliev (historian) |location=Brussels |year=1935 |title=Chronique anonyme de Cambridge |encyclopedia=Byzance et les Arabes |volume=1 |pages=342–46}}</ref>

==Editions==
