{{use dmy dates|date=August 2015}} {{Infobox organization | name = Norsk filminstitutt | image = Filmens Hus dronningensgt oslo IMG 8672.JPG | caption = ''Filmens hus'', the NFI headquarters in Oslo | formation = {{Start date and years ago|1955|05|03|df=yes}} | type = [[Government agency]] | headquarters = [[Oslo]], [[Norway]] | coords = {{coord|59|54|34|N|10|44|45|E|type:landmark|display=inline,title}} | region_served = Norway | language = [[Norwegian language|Norwegian]] | leader_title = CEO | leader_name = Sindre Guldvog | key_people = | parent_organization = [[Ministry of Culture (Norway)|Royal Norwegian Ministry of Culture]] | num_staff = 100 | website = {{url|www.nfi.no}} }}
The '''Norwegian Film Institute''' ({{lang-no|Norsk filminstitutt}}) was founded in 1955 to support and develop the [[Cinema of Norway|Norwegian film industry]]. On 1 April 2008, it was merged with Norwegian Film Fund, Norwegian Film Development, and Norwegian Film Commission to form the "'new' Norwegian Film Institute" under the auspices of the [[Ministry of Culture (Norway)|Royal Norwegian Ministry of Culture]].<ref name="history">{{cite web|url=http://www.nfi.no/english/aboutnfi/about/a_brief_history_of_the_norwegian_film_institute|title=A Brief History of the Norwegian Film Institute|date=8 April 2011|publisher=Norwegian Film Institute|accessdate=5 November 2012}}</ref>
The NFI is a member of the [[International Federation of Film Archives]], the International Council of Educational Media, [[European Film Academy]], and Scandinavian Films, and represents Norway in [[Eurimages]] and the [[European Audiovisual Observatory]].
A large amount of the library's archives are stored in a high-security bunker in [[Mo i Rana]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Lost 1927 Disney Christmas film found in Norway|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2014/dec/11/disney-empty-socks-short-film-found-norway|publisher=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=13 December 2014|date=11 December 2014}}</ref>
