{{distinguish|Utu}}
[[File:A classic circular form spider's web.jpg|thumb|upright=1.3|Uttu was envisioned as a spider spinning a web.{{sfn|Black|Green|1992|page=182}}{{sfn|Jacobsen|1987|page=184}}]]
{{Mesopotamian myth|expanded=3}}

'''Uttu''' is an [[Sumerian religion|ancient Sumerian goddess]] associated with weaving.{{sfn|Black|Green|1992|page=182}} The same [[cuneiform script|cuneiform]] symbol used to write her name was also used to write the Sumerian word for "[[spider]]",{{sfn|Black|Green|1992|page=182}} indicating that Uttu was probably envisioned as a spider spinning a web.{{sfn|Black|Green|1992|page=182}} She appears primarily in the myth of ''[[Enki]] and Ninsikila'', in which she resists the sexual advances of her father Enki by ensconcing herself inside her [[Spider web|web]], but he convinces her to let him in using a gift of fresh produce and the promise that he will marry her. Enki then intoxicates her with [[beer]] and [[rape]]s her. She is rescued by Enki's wife [[Ninhursag]], who removes Enki's [[semen]] from her [[vagina]] and plants it in the ground, resulting in the growth of eight new plants, which Enki later eats.

==Mythology==
===''Enki and Ninsikila''===
In the version of ''[[Enki]] and Ninsikila'' from [[Nippur]], Uttu is the daughter of Enki and [[Ninkurra]],{{sfn|Jacobsen|1987|page=184}} but, in another version, Ninkurra instead gives birth to [[Nin-imma]],{{sfn|Jacobsen|1987|page=184}} who mates with her father Enki and gives birth to Uttu as a result.{{sfn|Jacobsen|1987|page=184}} Uttu matures and becomes "shapely and decorous".{{sfn|Jacobsen|1987|page=184}} Enki's wife [[Ninhursag]] warns Uttu that Enki will try to seduce her, as he has done with all his other daughters.{{sfn|Jacobsen|1987|page=184}} Uttu fortifies herself inside her [[Spider web|web]] and, when Enki comes to seduce her, she forces him to promise that he will marry her before she will have sex with him.{{sfn|Jacobsen|1987|page=184}} As marriage gifts, Uttu demands that Enki give her fruits and vegetables.{{sfn|Jacobsen|1987|page=184}} Enki finds a gardener, who demands that, in exchange for the fruits and vegetables, Enki must fill his [[irrigation]] ditches with water.{{sfn|Jacobsen|1987|page=184}} Enki fills the ditches and the gardener gives him the produce.{{sfn|Jacobsen|1987|page=184}}

Enki brings the produce to Uttu, who happily admits him into her web,{{sfn|Jacobsen|1987|page=184}} but Enki gives Uttu [[beer]] to make her drunk and then [[rape]]s her.{{sfn|Jacobsen|1987|page=184}} Uttu screams and Ninhursag comes to rescue her.{{sfn|Jacobsen|1987|page=184}} Ninhursag removes Enki's [[semen]] from Uttu's vagina and plants it in the ground,{{sfn|Jacobsen|1987|page=184}} causing eight plants to rise.{{sfn|Jacobsen|1987|page=184}} Later, Enki sees the plants and is annoyed because he does not recognize them.{{sfn|Jacobsen|1987|page=184}} [[Isimud]], Enki's ''sukkal'', or personal attendant, arrives, names each of the plants, and gives them to Enki to eat.{{sfn|Jacobsen|1987|page=184}} The account ends with the declaration that "Enki determined the nature of the grasses" and "had them know it in their hearts."{{sfn|Jacobsen|1987|page=184}}

